Context: Banking System

Example: A bank's Customer Management system has two classes representing different customer profiles (e.g., Individual and Corporate).

In this scenario, interfaces come into play. The interface for the Individual Customer class might look like:

```
INTERFACENAME IndividualCustomerInterface
{
  ABAPFUNCTIONNAME checkeligibility;
  // Other methods specific to individual customers
}
```

This interface defines a set of method names (e.g., `checkeligibility`), which the two customer classes, Individual and Corporate, can implement differently.

In this banking example, interfaces ensure that the core functionality for managing customer profiles is decoupled from the specific implementation details of each customer type.
